{{Quote|In opposition to Kad Ha'rangir stood the sloth-god Arasuum, who sought to tempt the clans and drag them down into stagnation and idle consumption.|[[Vilnau Teupt]]|<ref name="TEGW">''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]''</ref>}}
'''Arasuum''' was a [[God/Legends|deity]] in the ancient [[Mandalorian religion]]. Known as the sloth-god, the [[Mandalorian/Legends|Mandalorians]] viewed Arasuum as the personification of stagnation,<ref name="TMPaC" /> who tempted the ancient clans to engage in idle consumption.<ref name="TEGW" /> Opposing Arasuum was the god [[Kad Ha'rangir]], who embodied the [[Universe/Legends|universal]] opportunity for change and growth that destruction created. Mandalorian mythology held that Arasuum and Kad Ha'rangir waged an eternal war against one another.<ref name="TMPaC" />

The Mandalorians who believed in these ancient gods waged ritual warfare as a means of worship<ref name="HotM">{{InsiderCite|80|The History of the Mandalorians: Exploring the Evolution of a Mighty Race of Warriors}}</ref> toward Kad Ha'rangir, whose ideals they served,<ref name="TEGW" /> taking on the name [[Mandalorian Crusaders]] as a reflection of the holiness embodied by the conflict they engaged in.<ref name="HotM" /> By fighting wars in the destroyer god's name, the Mandalorians sought to earn Kad Ha'rangir's favor, and defied the temptations of Arasuum.<ref name="TEGW" />

However, over [[Time/Legends|time]], the belief in Arasuum and the worship of Kad Ha'rangir fell out of favor. After witnessing a spiritual vision on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Shogun (planet)|Shogun]], the Mandalorian [[Mandalore (title)/Legends|leader]] known as [[Mandalore the Indomitable]] decreed that the act of war itself would be the center of Mandalorian worship, and that to wage war was to be divine,<ref name="TEGW" /> though the worship of war, too, would decline as the [[Standard century/Legends|centuries]] passed.<ref name="TMPaC" /> Despite this, Arasuum and the Mandalorian gods of old would not be forgotten: millennia later, in [[19 BBY/Legends|19 BBY]], the Mandalorian [[Soldier/Legends|soldier]] [[Kal Skirata]] knew of their former place in Mandalorian mythology,<ref name="O66">''[[Order 66: A Republic Commando Novel]]''</ref> and the [[Historian/Legends|historian]] [[Vilnau Teupt]] recounted their importance to the early Mandalorians during his [[Industry, Honor, Savagery: Shaping the Mandalorian Soul|keynote speech]] at the four hundred twelfth [[Proceedings of Galactic Anthropology and History]] at the [[Brentaal Academy]] in [[24 ABY/Legends|24 ABY]].<ref name="TEGW" />

==Behind the scenes==
Arasuum was first mentioned in the article titled ''[[The Mandalorians: People and Culture]]''. [[Author/Legends|Authored]] by [[Karen Traviss]], the article was published [[February]] [[2006]] as part of the [[Star Wars Insider 86|eighty-sixth issue]] of the [[Star Wars Insider]] magazine. Arasuum was also mentioned in the later reference book, ''[[The Essential Guide to Warfare]]'', written by [[Jason Fry]] and [[Paul R. Urquhart]], and published [[April 3]], [[2012]].

